<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>down-turn • turn-down</xh5><p> <i>down-turn—</i>a decline, especially in economic or business activity: The economy has already demonstrated that it can suffer a mild <u>downturn</u> in manufacturing.</p><p><i>turn-down—</i>1. the turned-down part of smth.: I showed him the <u>turn-down</u>, only the turn-down, of your note. 2. said of the action of rejecting: I look back on that period of sour welcome and curt <u>turn-down</u> with feelings I cannot express. 3. <i>(U.S.)</i> smb. who is rejected, especially as unfit for military service: We’ve gotten a lot of <u>turndowns</u>, yeah; but we’ve gotten guys who’re willing, too. 4. <i>= down-turn: </i>How far Americans could continue running up debts during an economic <u>turndown</u> was not clear.</p> </entry>
